comments.text:
+Panneer Yuvaraja OK, so let me begin.
If your just starting out, your going to want to have a good base to build 
from. Find out how many calories you require daily to maintain current 
weight, then aim for around 10-15% surplus to bulk. If you want to lose 
weight, aim for around 10-15% deficit.
As far as BCAA's are concerned, don't worry about them too much. Just look 
for a whey protein that includes them.
As the hodgetwins referenced, Optimum Nutrition whey protein is a good 
place to start, currently what i am using and it includes BCAA's (Branched 
Chained Amino Acids) and Glutamine. 
Creatine is a good addition, but not essential at first, Just make sure you 
cycle with it. Casein Protein as far as im concerned is not really required 
for a couple reasons, adds another $100 a month to your protein bill, and 
unless your training twice a day the use of it is not warranted, all it 
does is slowly digests in your stomach, essentially it turns into a gel in 
your stomach, because sleep is the longest you usually go with out eating.
If your going to use a pre/post-work out, look for one that includes EAA's 
(Essential Amino Acids) Helps with recovery, these are the ones your body 
can NOT produce naturally. I use Amino Energy by Optimum Nutrition.

The 3 things i use in terms of supplements are:
Optimum Nutrition whey Protein.
Optimum Nutrition Amino Energy.
Axis Labs Monohydrate Creatine.

One more thing, A clean diet helps a lot.

Hope this helps dude.

comments.text:
It's all almost useless if you're eating a lot. The problem is eating a lot 
may be complicated for many people. Back when I was getting big I would eat 
a lot, all the time. A lot was something like, you go to a pizza place and 
ask for the largest pizza with a lot of meat and eat everything by 
yourself. Then get some dessert. Then 3 hours later at home you eat a full 
plate of pasta with chicken of beef. My "breakfast" many times was 250g of 
spaghetti with 2 chicken breasts and 100g of parmesan cheese, all that with 
a lot of either tomato sauce or cheese sauce. No faggoty lettuce and low 
fat stuff. After you get big, then you switch to supplements, and go to a 
"normal" healthy diet, with vegetables and lean meats, etc. It's kinda like 
this, 1 kilogram of meat has 5 grams of creatine. But very few people eat 
this much meat. And if you're not working out a lot, all the fat in this 
amount of meat will make you fatter. So it's cheaper and wiser to eat 
creatine as a supplement. Also, 1 liter of milk (about a third of a gallon) 
has a little more protein than 1 scoop of whey protein. But it's much 
easier to just drink one glass of whey. 98% of the people I see rely too 
much on "products", and they don't grow (unless the products are steroids). 
In order to make crazy gains naturally, you have to eat A LOT of all kinds 
of foods. This "nice and clean" only makes you grow considerably when 
you're on heavy supplements and steroids.

Creatine does not make you weaker.  It's used so your ADP, turns into ATP, 
and you have more energy in your muscles to train harder.  Water carries 
ATP to muscles and stores it there, so yes you have water weight there, but 
the fact is, the more ATP your body has, the harder you are going to train, 
and the more gains you will realise.  It's dependent on the person too, 
some people have a high baseline of ATP in their body as is, and taking 
creatine won't help them and they will just add water weight.
